The paper deals with the design of CONGEST algorithms for solving fundamental graph problems in restricted network topologies, which falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also considers the relationship between low-congestion shortcuts and graph parameters such as chordality, diameter, and clique-width, which are topics in Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) and Graph Theory (cs.GT). The paper presents algorithms for constructing low-congestion shortcuts, which involves network topology and communication, making it relevant to Networked Systems (cs.NI) as well. Finally, the paper discusses the complexity of constructing MST in small-diameter graphs, which is a topic in Computational Geometry (cs.CG).
